# I18n Conventions

## Use the Framework

Rails ships **I18n** — use **`t()`** / **`I18n.t`** for user-visible static copy instead of scattering raw English in ERB and helpers. Domain data (`@article.title`) stays out of locale files; **labels, buttons, flashes, and validation messages** belong in **`config/locales`**.

Canonical patterns: **`skills/writing-i18n/references/patterns.md`**. Mailer subjects and mail-scoped keys: **`skills/writing-mailers/references/patterns.md`** (subjects) + writing-i18n for key shape. Pundit flash messages: **`skills/writing-policies/references/patterns.md`** § I18n for Policy Messages.

## Keys

- **Scope by feature** — `articles.index.title`, `comments.form.submit`, not a flat `title_472`.
- **`activerecord`** — attributes and errors live under Rails’ expected structure for `human_attribute_name` and form errors.
- **Lazy lookup in templates** — `t(".heading")` resolves relative to the view path; use for page-specific copy.
- **Absolute keys** — shared partials, helpers, controllers (`flash`), mailers — `t("articles.published_notice")`.

## Anti-Patterns

| Anti-Pattern | Instead |
|-------------|---------|
| `"Hello " + user.name + "!"` in ERB | `t("greeting", name: user.name)` with `%{name}` in YAML |
| `t("foo.#{key}.bar")` with unbounded `key` | Fixed keys, enum, or explicit allowlist |
| User-facing strings only in English in `en.yml` and hardcoded elsewhere | One approach per app; translate keys consistently |
| Storing canonical copy in the DB for static UI | Locale files for static strings; DB for user-authored content |

## What This Rule Is Not

Translation vendor workflows, TMS sync, and client-side i18n stacks — out of scope. This plugin documents **Rails I18n** conventions only.
